"1113":"1113","24 June 1082":"24 June 1082","Blingel, Pas-Calés, Heuts-d'Franche, Française":"Blingel, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","Blingel, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Blingel, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"BLINGEL","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from <i>Klingel</i> ‘small bell’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a maker of handbells or alternatively a nickname for an incessant chatterer."],"variants":[{"name":"Klingele","meanings":["German: variant of   Klingel  ."]}]},{"name":"Louis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hlōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>wīg</i> ‘war’. It was very common in French royal and noble families.  Louis I  (  778–840 ) was the son of Charlemagne, who ruled as both King of France and Holy Roman Emperor. Altogether, the name was borne by sixteen kings of France up to the French Revolution, in which Louis XVI perished. Louis XIV, ‘the Sun King’ (  1638–1715 ), reigned for seventy-two years (  1643–1715 ), presiding in the middle part of his reign over a period of unparalleled French power and prosperity. In modern times Louis is also found in the English-speaking world (usually pronounced ‘<b>loo</b>-ee’). In Britain the Anglicized form   Lewis   is rather more common, whereas in America the reverse is true."],"variants":[{"name":"Lewie","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of   Louis  , or a pet form of   Lewis ."]},{"name":"Louie","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Lewie   or   Louis  , currently in fashion."]},{"name":"Lewi","meanings":["name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hlōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>wīg</i> ‘war’. It was very common in French royal and noble families.  Louis I  (  778–840 ) was the son of Charlemagne, who ruled as both King of France and Holy Roman Emperor. Altogether, the name was borne by sixteen kings of France up to the French Revolution, in which Louis XVI perished. Louis XIV, ‘the Sun King’ (  1638–1715 ), reigned for seventy-two years (  1643–1715 ), presiding in the middle part of his reign over a period of unparalleled French power and prosperity. In modern times Louis is also found in the English-speaking world (usually pronounced ‘<b>loo</b>-ee’). In Britain the Anglicized form   Lewis   is rather more common, whereas in America the reverse is true."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Louis DE BLINGEL was born in 1059, in Blingel, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, his father, Gautier de BLINDEL, was 34 and his mother, Beatrix de Blangy, was 20. He married Marie DE TANGRY in 1080. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1114, in his hometown, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1059–1114":"1059–1114","1061–1113":"1061–1113","1065–1098":"1065–1098","1082–1135":"1082–1135","1084–1142":"1084–1142","1083–1135":"1083–1135","1025–Male":"1025–Surnud","1039–1085":"1039–1085","1080":"1080","1098":"1098","1142":"1142","1065":"1065","1085":"1085","1084":"1084","1083":"1083","1061":"1061","1082":"1082","1039":"1039","1049":"1049","1059":"1059","1114":"1114","1025":"1025","1135":"1135","1113":"1113","24 June 1082":"24.